/* top */ Removing "sometimes known as Thomas Hobbes of Malmesbury". No, he really wasn't. That a book of his tracts was published after his death with a title mentioning Malmesbury says very little about him being "known" that way, considering what book titles were typically like in the 17th century; i. e, they were incredibly verbose. If he was known as anything to do with Malmesbury, it was as "the sage of Malmesbury". None of it belongs in the first sentence, anyway.

The claim that John Donne was George Herbert’s godfather and “stood in” (presumably as a father-figure or guardian of some sort) lacks credibility.  Amy M. Charles’s biography of Herbert is apparently cited as the source of the date of Herbert’s father’s death; it makes no reference to Donne serving as godfather.  The other citation is to a web document by Patrick Moore, which asserts that Donne was Herbert’s godfather but cites no evidence or source for this claim.

I made two amendments because Lord Byron being described simply as "English" is not accurate but is rather a clumsy over-simplification of his complex national identity.

He himself identified as at least partly Scottish, saying he was "half a Scot by birth, and bred/A whole one". In this, he vocally identified as a Scot. He was educated for a time at Aberdeen Grammar School and reportedly had a Scottish accent (albeit a faint one) throughout his life.

The Gordons were of course a family wit...

English is a more accurate description. See Talk page. Byron was born in London, spent a few years there, lived a few short years in Scotland before returning to his ancestral home in England at the age of 10. He never set foot in Scotland again.

As other people editing the article have said, "British" is the most accurate, though imperfect, term to reflect Lord Byron's complex national identity with regard to Scotland and England.

The assertion that England was Byron's "ancestral home" ignores the prevailing links that Byron felt to Scotland and the complexity of his own identity. His identity was far more complex than simply recognising where he was born.

The official death date of John Stuart Mill, although widely reported by unofficial sources as being in May 8, 1873, is actually May 7, 1873. This information is taken for the official entry in the Registres de l'Etat civil d'Avignon. A copy to this document appears in Emile Thouverez, Stuart Mill. 4.ed. Paris: Bloud & Cie, 1908, p. 23, and a reference to this document can also be found on Friedrich Hayek's Hayek on Mill, Sandra Peart (ed.), (The University of Chicago Press, 2015, p. 270).

/* Context and background */ The essays I deleted are not well known by George Eliot scholars and definitely should not be included among the essential works otherwise included in this reference list. There are hundreds of articles and books published on George Eliot. There are 36 full-length biographies alone. Only the most cited should be included here. I will be adding other essential readings, including George Eliot: Interviews and Recollections by K. K. Collins, 2010.
/* Further reading */ removed an essay not well known by Eliot scholars and certainly not important enough to include here.

/* External links */ Added link to 50 years of digitized back issues of The George Eliot Review, a peer-reviewed journal published by the George Eliot Fellowship in partnership with Dr. Beverley Rilett of the University of Nebraska-Lincoln. George Bernard Shaw held both British and Irish citizenship and was born in Ireland when it was still part of the United Kingdom. He also chose to spend his last days in the United Kingdom when Ireland had gained its independence, which shows a certain attachment to Britain, even during the Second World War, when the United Kingdom was threatened by the Germans. We cannot simply say that he is just an Irish playwright.

Beckett rejected Lucia before her diagnosis, and her mental health was never once brought up as reason for rejection. Changing birth place from 'Northern Ireland' to 'Ireland,' as MacNeice was born in 1907, over a decade before the partition of Ireland, and thus, at the time of his birth, 'Northern Ireland' did not only not exist, but would have been a ludicrous suggestion. Liken it to a post-Brexit suggestion of giving independence to the north of England.

'Anglo-Irish' poet, rather than 'British' poet. The latter is far more vague, and would easily be mistaken for English. Anglo-Irish takes into account his birthplace, family origins, childhood, the inescapable Irish context of his life; but also the 'Anglo' placed him within his class and religion within Irish society.

'British poet' to 'Irish poet.' His work cannot be understood properly outside of an Irish cultural context. 'British' refers to nationality and is far more vague: can also mean English, Welsh etc
